                        "<div style='text-align: justify;'>When clothes are soaked in soapy water, the hydrophobic tails attach themselves to the oily dirt, while the hydrophilic heads stay in the water. They surround the dirt particle, forming a structure called a <b>micelle</b>.</div>",
                        "<div style='text-align: justify;'>The micelles suspend the dirt as a colloid. Upon mechanical agitation (scrubbing), these micelles detach from the cloth surface and are washed away with the water, cleaning the fabric.</div>",
